# Figma Factory Quality

This rule applies to any skill that generates Figma components from
scratch — currently
[`generate-uds-figma-component`](../skills/generate-uds-figma-component/SKILL.md),
[`new-component`](../skills/new-component/SKILL.md),
[`figma-component-card`](../skills/figma-component-card/SKILL.md), and
any future factory variants. It captures the **process quality gates**
that emerge from designer feedback on factory runs — they're not
obvious from the Plugin API alone, and they're not UDS-specific.

These rules are component-agnostic AND design-system-agnostic. The
specific UDS state constructions (what hover looks like, how focus
rings layer, etc.) live in
[`uds-design-language.mdc`](./uds-design-language.mdc). This rule is
about the *process* of getting any factory build to a quality
threshold; that rule is about the *output* a UDS factory build should
resolve to.

## 1. State design contract

If the component has multiple **visual states** (Default / Hover /
Focus / Filled / Error / Disabled / Read-only / Loading / Selected / …),
Phase A's model MUST specify the **full visual treatment** of each
state, not just its token-role mapping.

### Token-role mapping alone is insufficient

`State=Hover: border bound to outline-hover` is necessary but it
doesn't tell the factory:

- Is the border the **only** visual cue, or is there also an outer ring?
- If a ring, what's the gap (px) and ring thickness (px), and which
  surface variable acts as the gap layer?
- What's the stroke alignment (`INSIDE` / `CENTER` / `OUTSIDE`)?
- Does the border change thickness (e.g. 1 px → 2 px)?
- How does the state's visual weight compare to its neighbors (Hover
  should typically be *less* prominent than Focus, *more* than Default)?

Without these, the factory will guess differently every run.

### Required Phase A state row shape

For every named state, the model must include a row with at least these
columns:

| Column | What it captures |
|---|---|
| State name | `Default`, `Hover`, `Focus`, `Filled`, `Selected`, `Error`, `Disabled`, `Read-only`, `Loading`, etc. |
| Background | bound token (or "unchanged") |
| Border color | bound token |
| Border weight | px (1, 2, etc.) |
| Stroke alignment | `INSIDE` / `CENTER` / `OUTSIDE` |
| Effects | for each: type, spread (px), bound color variable, **and layering order** (which sits on top) |
| Text fill | bound token (or "unchanged") |
| Cursor | `pointer` / `not-allowed` / `default` |
| Visual hierarchy note | how this state's prominence compares to its neighbors |

The layering-order column is non-negotiable for any state that uses
stacked effects (e.g. a focus ring with a gap layer). Two stacked drop
shadows render differently depending on which is in front; specifying
"spread=1 surface-main + spread=3 outline-focus" without saying which
is on top is ambiguous.

### Focus / ring states are an offset, gapped, resizing ring — not a border

A focus (or any ring-style selection) state is NOT a thickened border on
the element. It is a separate ring that sits in a gap *outside* the
element edge and **resizes with the element**. Thickening the element's
own border (1 px → 2 px in the focus color) reads as a heavier border,
not a focus ring — it was the Metric Card focus miss.

Canonical values live in
[`uds-design-language.mdc`](./uds-design-language.mdc) §6 (ring color
`border-outline-focus-visible`, **2 px gap**, gapped construction for
every element including cards). The Figma build of construction A
(CSS `outline` + `outline-offset`) is:

- An absolute-positioned `focus-outline` frame, child of **the focused
  element box itself** — the bordered field / trigger / control that
  takes focus, NOT the variant wrapper or any label+field+helper stack
  around it. Parenting the ring to the outer wrapper makes it track the
  wrapper's size and vertical extent instead of the box, so it drifts
  off the box the moment the wrapper grows (a wrapped label, a helper
  row). The ring rings the box; it lives inside the box.
- Non-flow positioning that depends on the box's layout type: when the
  box is an **auto-layout frame**, set `layoutPositioning = 'ABSOLUTE'`
  so the ring doesn't join the layout flow (the combobox field is
  auto-layout). When the box is a **plain (non-auto-layout) frame**, the
  ring is just a normally-positioned child — do NOT set
  `layoutPositioning = 'ABSOLUTE'` (non-auto-layout children don't flow,
  and setting it there can throw); the toggle track is a plain frame, so
  its ring is correctly `AUTO`-positioned + constraints-driven.
- `constraints = { horizontal: 'STRETCH', vertical: 'STRETCH' }` on both
  axes is mandatory **in both cases** — this is what makes the ring
  resize with the box. `MIN` (or any non-`STRETCH` value) pins the ring
  at a fixed size so it stops resizing — the combobox 2026-06-08 miss
  shipped a `MIN` `328×56` ring that didn't grow when the field widened.
  A focus variant whose ring constraints are not `STRETCH`/`STRETCH`
  fails the gate.
- Inset by −(gap + ringWeight) on every side (2 px gap + 2 px ring →
  `x = y = −4`, size = element + 8).
- `fills = []`, stroke bound to `outline-focus-visible`,
  `strokeAlign = 'INSIDE'`, corner radius bound concentric to the
  element's (element radius + inset).
- **`clipsContent = false` on every ancestor up to and including the
  component set** — not just the immediate parent. The ring renders
  *outside* the box bounds via its negative inset, so any one clipping
  ancestor shaves it wherever the variant sits flush to that ancestor's
  edge. The combobox 2026-06-08 miss had the immediate parent unclipped
  but the field box AND the enclosing component set both clipping, so
  the ring was cut at the set's left edge (and top/bottom on the option
  set). Walk element box → variant → component set and confirm every one
  is `clipsContent = false`.

The element keeps its normal Default border underneath, and you build
this ring for every focus (and ring-style) variant — per tone.

### The ring is a pure overlay — it never changes the box footprint

Because the ring is absolute-positioned with a negative inset, it must
never add to the element's size. Every variant's box stays the **same
size** whether or not it carries a ring — a Focused variant is exactly
as wide and tall as its Default sibling. Do NOT widen / pad a variant to
"make room" for the ring; the ring overlays outside the box and the
sibling-consistent footprint is the contract. If a ring appears clipped,
the fix is an unclipped ancestor chain (above), never a resized box.

When an audit or inspection looks for this ring, match it
**structurally** (absolute frame, empty fills, stroke bound to
`outline-focus-visible`), never by a name substring — `/outline/`
collides with Material glyph names like `people_outline`
([`uds-figma-plugin-api-gotchas.mdc`](./uds-figma-plugin-api-gotchas.mdc)
§15).

### Source the canonical visuals from the design language doc

For UDS factory runs specifically: don't re-derive state visuals from
scratch. Read
[`uds-design-language.mdc`](./uds-design-language.mdc) (or the
designer-facing
[`uds-docs/app/(site)/design-language/page.tsx`](../../uds-docs/app/(site)/design-language/page.tsx))
and bind the Phase A model to its canon. That doc was derived from
every existing component CSS, with known inconsistencies surfaced
explicitly — so the factory output stays in dialect with the system.

If the design language doc doesn't cover the state the component
needs (e.g. a brand new selection treatment), surface that as a
Phase A question for the designer rather than inventing one.

### Read the existing component's CSS as a sanity check

When the factory is redesigning an *existing* UDS component,
`uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/<id>.css` already encodes that
component's specific construction. Compare it against the design
language canon — if they agree, use the canon; if they disagree,
surface the gap (it's likely a known inconsistency the design language
doc lists, but might be a new one).

## 2. Validation is machine-verified, not claimed

The Phase C quality-gate report MUST run an audit script over the
post-build state. Counts and claims (unbound paints, missing properties,
variant mismatches) come from the script's return value, never from
memory.

### Minimum mandatory audit before Phase C report

A read-only `use_figma` call that:

1. Walks every variant of every component set the factory created.
2. For every fill, stroke, and effect color on every descendant
   (excluding nested instances of library components — those are
   out of scope), reports whether the paint is bound to a variable.
3. **Per-side spacing audit (all five properties).** For every
   auto-layout frame the factory created, report whether each of
   `paddingTop`, `paddingBottom`, `paddingLeft`, `paddingRight`, and
   `itemSpacing` is bound to a `uds-space` variable or carries a raw
   numeric value. Per-side, not per-axis pair. See
   [`uds-figma-plugin-api-gotchas.mdc`](./uds-figma-plugin-api-gotchas.mdc)
   §5 for the underlying API truth — there is no `paddingHorizontal`
   in the Plugin API; a script can bind the horizontal pair and
   silently leave the vertical pair as raw pixels.
4. **Effect-style binding audit.** For every node where
   `effects.length > 0`, report whether `effectStyleId` is set. Both
   conditions matter: an unbound `effects = [...]` literal renders
   visually but escapes any check that only looks at `effects.length`.
   See
   [`uds-figma-plugin-api-gotchas.mdc`](./uds-figma-plugin-api-gotchas.mdc)
   §6 for the audit signature.
5. **Per-variant INSTANCE_SWAP defaults audit.** For every component
   property registered with type `INSTANCE_SWAP`, walk every variant
   in the set and report which one(s) still hold the factory's
   universal default rather than the per-variant default the model
   specified. This catches the "every icon shipped as the same
   placeholder" failure mode where the technical wiring (component
   property exists, INSTANCE_SWAP type, default points at a real
   wrapper) is correct but the per-variant semantic differentiation
   (Stepper `complete` → `check`, `error` → `priority_high`) was
   never baked in via `setProperties` per variant. The model file
   under `.cursor/state/component-factory/<componentId>.md` is the
   source of truth for "what each variant should default to."
6. **Tone-bearing adornment coverage (content vs control split).** For
   every component with a `Tone` / status / state variant axis, walk each
   tone/state variant and check each color-carrying adornment against the
   §6 content-vs-control rule:
   - **Content / status adornments** (status dot, leading or secondary
     icon glyph, trend icon + text, accent bar) must bind that variant's
     tone family (`text-{tone}` / `icon-{tone}` / `surface-{tone}`;
     Neutral → `*-secondary`, Disabled → `*-disabled`). Report any bound
     to a foreign tone, and any content icon NOT following tone on
     Error / Disabled / Read-only. Catches the "trend stuck `success`
     green across all five tones" Metric Card failure.
   - **Control affordances** (chevron, clear / dismiss button, stepper
     caret — interactive control icons) follow usability, not validity:
     they MUST be `icon-disabled` on a Disabled variant, but are EXPECTED
     to stay neutral / `icon-interactive` on an Error variant — do NOT
     flag a non-tone control color in Error (a red chevron is the bug,
     not the fix). Report a control affordance still `icon-interactive`
     on a Disabled variant (the combobox 2026-06-08 miss, where every
     icon was pinned to `icon-interactive` across all states).
   - **Inverse / saturated surfaces (Selected / Pressed / Open /
     prominent-tone).** On any variant whose surface fills to
     `surface-interactive-default` / `-active` / `-hover`, a prominent
     `surface-{tone}`, or `surface-inverse`, EVERY foreground must resolve
     to the inverse family — text → `text-inverse`, and every icon /
     chevron / dot → `icon-inverse` (SHAPE_FILL scope, never `text-inverse`
     on an icon). Report any foreground on a filled surface still bound to a
     non-inverse family (the nav-header 2026-06-16 miss: selected menu rows,
     the pressed tile, and the open title-area all kept `icon-interactive`
     glyphs that vanished into the blue fill). Determine "filled surface"
     from the fill resolved on the node's OWN box or nearest
     surface-painting ancestor — NOT from the presence of inverse text
     elsewhere in the component (a white badge count on a light pill is not
     the leading glyph's background; that false signal blanked the My-Work
     `+` on 2026-06-16). See
     [`uds-design-language.mdc`](./uds-design-language.mdc) §4.1.
7. **Nested-instance exposure coverage.** For every nested DS instance
   the model marked designer-reachable, walk every variant and report
   any where `isExposedInstance !== true`. Instantiate the set once and
   confirm `instance.exposedInstances` lists each reachable wrapper.
   Catches the partial-coverage trap where the primary icon is exposed
   but a secondary affordance is not — the Metric Card run exposed the
   headline icon but left the overflow `menu` and the `trend` icon
   unexposed, so the designer couldn't change the menu glyph or the
   trend direction. Exposing the main icon is necessary, not
   sufficient: enumerate ALL reachable nested instances and expose
   each.

   **Proactive half — sealed control-bearing instances (don't trust the
   model).** The check above only fires on instances the model *flagged*
   reachable, so a pre-versioning draft or a forgotten instance slips
   through invisibly. ALSO walk every nested instance independently and
   classify it: an instance is **control-bearing** if it is a
   first-class `udc-*` component OR a `_udc-<id>_*` subpart that carries
   its own consumer-relevant `componentPropertyDefinitions` — a VARIANT
   axis, an editable TEXT prop, a meaningful BOOLEAN, or an
   INSTANCE_SWAP. A control-bearing instance that is NEITHER
   `isExposedInstance === true` NOR has those props hoisted to top-level
   host properties is **sealed** — a component that looks finished but
   can't be driven. This is the global-search 2026-06-09 miss: it passed
   every other gate while its nested `_udc-global-search_trigger`
   (`State`, `Filled`, placeholder, value) and `_udc-global-search_popover`
   (content variant) were sealed, so a consumer could only toggle `Open`.
   **Carve-out — soft flag, not hard fail:** a purely decorative or
   structural nested instance with no consumer reason to set anything (a
   static divider, an ornamental fixed glyph) reports as a review note,
   not a failure. The judgment ("would a consumer need to set this?")
   stays with the designer; the gate's job is to make every sealed
   control-bearing instance visible, not to force-expose ornament.
   Report `{ component, nodeId, nodeName, kind: 'sealed-controls' |
   'sealed-controls-review', availableProps }`.
8. **Focus-ring construction.** For every focus / ring-style variant,
   FIND the ring candidate **without pre-filtering on position** — match
   any descendant whose stroke is bound to `outline-focus-visible`, or an
   empty-fill stroked frame whose name starts with `focus`
   (`focus-outline`, `focus-wrapper`, …). Do NOT require
   `ABSOLUTE` in the *finder* — that's the property being tested, and a
   finder that requires it makes a mis-built in-layout ring invisible and
   the variant falsely pass with "0 rings" (the toggle 2026-06-09 blind
   spot: its ring was an `AUTO`-positioned `focus-wrapper`, so an
   absolute-only finder reported none). Never match by a bare `/outline/`
   name (collides with Material glyphs like `people_outline`). A focus
   variant with NO candidate ring fails (missing or thickened-border-only
   focus). For each candidate found, verify it is actually built to the
   §1 contract, not just present:
   - `constraints.horizontal === 'STRETCH'` AND `constraints.vertical ===
     'STRETCH'` (the resize guarantee, required regardless of box type).
     Report any ring pinned `MIN` / `CENTER` / `MAX` — it does not resize
     with the box.
   - `layoutPositioning === 'ABSOLUTE'` **only when the ring's parent is
     an auto-layout frame** (a flow child there is wrong). When the
     parent is a plain non-auto-layout frame, the ring is correctly
     `AUTO` + constraints-driven — do NOT flag it. Requiring `ABSOLUTE`
     unconditionally false-positives on plain-frame boxes like the toggle
     track (its ring is `AUTO`/`STRETCH` and correct).
   - Negative inset on every side (`x < 0`, `y < 0`, size ≈ box + 2·|inset|).
   - No clipping ancestor: walk the ring's parent chain up to and
     including the component set and report any node with
     `clipsContent === true`.
   - The ring's nearest non-absolute ancestor is the focused element box
     (the bordered field/trigger), not the variant wrapper.
   - **Grid-cell edge-ring exception.** A small cell tiled into a dense
     repeating grid (the `_udc-calendar-day` cell, and analogous tiled
     subcomponents) may instead carry the focus indicator as an **edge
     ring** — a stroke bound to `outline-focus-visible` on the focus
     variant's root box, no offset frame. Recognize that as a valid
     construction for grid cells and do NOT flag it as "missing ring" or
     "thickened-border-only." Carve-out is grid-cells-only: an edge ring
     on a normal inline control (button, field, link, checkbox) still
     fails — those use the gapped offset (design-language §6.2, §6.4).
   "Resizing" is a property to verify, not a word to assert — the
   combobox 2026-06-08 build shipped a `MIN`/`MIN`, clipped ring that
   passed the older presence-only gate. Report
   `{ ownerVariant, ringId, failing: [...] }` per ring.
9. **Label nesting + forwarding (form/labeled components).** For any
   component whose model class is a labeled field or control (the §9
   list), walk every variant and verify the field label is a **nested
   `udc-label` instance whose properties are forwarded to the
   consumer** — not raw text, and not a nested-but-unreachable instance:
   - Report any field label that is a raw TEXT node (or a raw
     text+required-dot pair) where `udc-label` exists. A field label
     drawn as raw text FAILS — it strands `udc-label`'s text / required
     / optional / leading-icon / right-slot properties and re-drifts its
     own text style. (This is the host-owned mistake of 2026-06-09 — the
     combobox shipped a static "Label" text node with no editable
     properties.)
   - For each nested `udc-label` instance, report whether its properties
     are reachable by the consumer: `isExposedInstance === true` OR the
     key properties (`text`, `required`, leading-icon, right-slot) are
     hoisted to top-level component properties on the host set. A nested
     label that is NEITHER exposed NOR hoisted FAILS — the consumer
     can't edit the label text, toggle required, or set the icon/badge
     (the original pre-2026-06-09 combobox defect). Resolve the main via
     `getMainComponentAsync()` and confirm the set name is `udc-label`;
     don't match on layer name alone.
   - Report whether the nested label's `tone` tracks the host's state
     (Error variant → `tone=Error`, Disabled → `tone=Disabled`). A
     field label stuck at `tone=Default` on an Error/Disabled variant
     fails.
   - This check does NOT fire when the component **being built is the
     standalone `udc-label` itself** — exempt a component set named
     `udc-label`.
   Report `{ ownerVariant, nodeId, kind: 'raw-text-field-label' | 'unforwarded-nested-label' | 'tone-not-tracking-state', detail }`.
10. **Field popover overlay (field-with-menu components).** For any
    component whose model opens a menu / listbox / popover (combobox,
    select, dropdown, autocomplete, date-picker), walk every open variant
    and verify the open surface is an overlay anchored to the field, not
    an in-flow sibling after the helper row. Report any open variant
    whose listbox/menu is an in-flow auto-layout child
    (`layoutPositioning !== 'ABSOLUTE'`) sitting after the helper row, or
    whose anchor leaves a gap between the field's bottom edge and the menu
    top. The combobox 2026-06-08 build shipped the menu as the last flow
    child after the helper row (field bottom y72 → helper y76 → menu y92)
    — it failed this. See §10. Report
    `{ ownerVariant, menuNodeId, kind: 'menu-in-flow' | 'menu-not-anchored-to-field' }`.
11. **Field-metrics conformance (field/control components).** For any
    component whose model class is a field or form control (text input,
    search, dropdown, combobox, text area, date picker, checkbox, radio,
    toggle), verify it conforms to the design-language field-metrics
    contract ([`uds-design-language.mdc`](./uds-design-language.mdc) §10):
    - the control's alignment/touch container equals the contract height
      (48 px for UDS) with the visible control vertically centered.
      Report a visible control stretched to the container height (a giant
      checkbox) AND a container shorter than the contract (the ~24 px
      checkbox / ~32 px toggle that breaks single-line alignment and the
      touch floor).
    - the label is the nested `udc-label` at the contract label style
      (defers to check 9 for nesting/forwarding; this check verifies the
      style matches the contract).
    - the helper text matches the contract helper style, and the
      label→control and control→helper gaps match the contract gap.
    Report `{ ownerVariant, nodeId, kind: 'container-height' | 'control-stretched' | 'label-style' | 'helper-style' | 'gap', expected, actual }`.
12. **Contract-block currency (every component with a contract).** The
    `<<UDS-FACTORY-CONTRACT v1>>` block in `descriptionMarkdown` is a
    derived view of the component — ANY section can drift, not just
    states. Parse the block and verify every machine-checkable section
    against the live component set:
    - **Variant axes.** Each `Variant axes:` line (`<Axis> — v1 | v2 …`)
      must match `componentPropertyDefinitions[Axis].variantOptions`
      exactly — same axis names, same value set, verbatim casing. A
      renamed value the block didn't follow (metric-card variants renamed
      to `Hovered`/`Focused` while the block still read `Hover`/`Focus`)
      fails here.
    - **States baseline.** Every value of the `State` axis must appear in
      the block's `States` section (as supported or `notApplicable`), and
      every state the block lists `supported` must be a real `State`
      option. Drift either way fails.
    - **Parts.** Each `Parts:` entry should name a region that exists as a
      node in the component (a layer/frame of that name). A listed part
      with no matching node is stale.
    - **Depends on (nested half).** Every first-class `udc-*` instance
      nested in the component (via `findAllWithCriteria` INSTANCE →
      `mainComponent` name, excluding this component's own `_udc-<id>_*`
      subparts) must appear in `Depends on`, and vice versa. A nested
      `udc-*` missing from the list (or a listed `nested` dep no longer
      present) fails. The "opens in popover / reveals" relationships are
      author-supplied and not failed for absence.
    - **Factory-version line.** The block's `Factory-version:` must equal
      the `factory_version` plugin-data stamp on the component.
    - **Required new sections.** The block must contain `Summary:` and
      `Depends on:` (added in factory-version 2026.06.09.7) and
      `Exposed properties:` (added in 2026.06.09.8). Absence of any of
      the three fails — a pre-2026.06.09.8 block is stale by definition.
    - **Exposed properties (vs the live exposure).** The
      `Exposed properties:` section lists what a consumer can set on the
      top-level instance. Its entries must match the controls actually
      exposed on the component — top-level `componentPropertyDefinitions`
      plus the forwarded props of every nested instance with
      `isExposedInstance === true`. A control-bearing nested instance the
      block claims exposed but that is sealed (check 7), or an exposed
      instance the block omits, fails. `none` is only valid when the
      component genuinely forwards nothing beyond its own top-level props.
    The prose sections (Summary text, behavioral Props, Events, Keyboard,
    Screen reader, Acceptance) are presence-checked only — non-empty and
    not a stub — because Figma can't verify their correctness; their
    currency is enforced by the regenerate-on-touch discipline
    ([`uds-factory-versioning.mdc`](./uds-factory-versioning.mdc)). Report
    `{ component, kind: 'variant-axis-drift' | 'state-drift' | 'part-missing' | 'depends-on-drift' | 'factory-version-mismatch' | 'missing-summary' | 'missing-depends-on' | 'missing-exposed-properties' | 'exposed-properties-drift' | 'empty-prose-section', section, expected, actual }`.
13. Returns a structured object with the count of unbound items and
    their `{ ownerVariant, nodeId, nodeName, kind }` per check.

#### Attribute every node to its owning component first (applies to ALL checks)

Every check above that inspects the host component's OWN nodes — cruft,
focus-ring construction, layer hygiene, exposure, raw fills — must first
exclude nodes that belong to a **nested DS instance**. A node returned
by `host.findAll(...)` can be owned by a nested `udc-*` instance (its
ring, its padding, its internal frames), and flagging it against the
host is a false positive. `skipInvisibleInstanceChildren = true` does
NOT reliably exclude these, and a `n.type !== 'INSTANCE'` filter misses
the case where the node itself is a plain frame but its *ancestor* is
the instance. Walk the parent chain and skip the node if any ancestor
is an `INSTANCE` (recipe in
[`uds-figma-plugin-api-gotchas.mdc`](./uds-figma-plugin-api-gotchas.mdc)
§14).

The focus-ring gate specifically must detect the ring **structurally**
(absolute-positioned frame, empty fills, stroke bound to
`outline-focus-visible`), NOT by a name substring like `/outline/` —
Material glyph names (`people_outline`, `add_circle_outline`) collide
with it (gotchas §15).

Failure mode: the Metric Card stamp-only upgrade audit flagged the
nested overflow button's own hidden focus ring as host cruft and tried
to delete it (atomic rollback). The ancestor-instance check and
structural ring detection both prevent this class of false positive.

#### Naming-convention gate (validate against the naming framework)

Every variant-axis name and every state / selection value the factory
emits MUST come from the design system's naming framework. For UDS that's
the canonical lists in
[`uds-naming-conventions.mdc`](./uds-naming-conventions.mdc) — §1 states
(`Default` / `Hovered` / `Focused` / `Pressed` / `Selected` / `Disabled`
/ `Loading` / `Error` / `Empty` / `Read-only` / `Dragged` /
`Indeterminate` / `Checked` / `Current`), §2 sizes, §3 tones, §4
emphasis. The audit walks each component set's
`componentPropertyDefinitions` and reports every VARIANT-axis value not
in the canonical set (the framework rule carries the drift→fix table —
`Hover`→`Hovered`, `Focus`/lowercase `focused`→`Focused`,
`Active`→`Pressed`-or-`Current`, a toggle on-state `Selected`→`Checked`,
any lowercase Figma value → Title Case). A rename is classified
`potentially-breaking` per
[`uds-figma-change-classification.mdc`](./uds-figma-change-classification.mdc)
and defaults to ask-user — never silently renamed. This gate is what
stops a new or re-factoried draft re-introducing the
`Focus`/`focused`/`Active`/`Selected`-on-a-toggle drift the older drafts
shipped. The gate is design-system-agnostic in shape — point it at
whatever naming framework the system defines; the canonical values live
in that rule, not here.

Membership is the test, not surface shape: a value fails because it is
not in the canonical set, hyphen or no hyphen. A clean SINGLE word that
names a different concern — `Editing` (a mode), `Open` / `Expanded`
(disclosure), `Selected` on a toggle on-state — fails this membership
check even though the hyphen smell test below would wave it through. The
hyphen test catches *compound* mushes (`Open-Empty`); this membership
check catches *single-word* ones. Both must run — the data-field
2026-06-10 `State = … | Editing` slipped a hand-rolled Phase C that ran
neither half.

**Compound-value smell test (one-concern-per-axis, §8).** Beyond the
canonical-value check, the gate flags variant values that mush two
concerns into one axis. A hyphenated value on the **`State` axis**
(`Open-Empty`, `Open-Typed`) is a HARD fail: canonical states never
contain a hyphen, so a hyphen there is always two dimensions wearing one
name (the global-search 2026-06-09 mush — disclosure + content +
interaction in a single `State`). A hyphenated value on **any other
axis** is a SOFT review flag, not a fail — some are one legitimate
concept (`Parent-collapsed` on a `Kind` axis). The fix is to split the
concern into its own axis per §8, classified `potentially-breaking` (a
variant restructure) and defaulting to ask-user. Report
`{ component, axis, value, kind: 'mushed-state-axis' | 'compound-value-review' }`.

The Phase C report's tool-emitted gates table is populated from that
return value. If the audit hasn't run, the report can't be emitted.

### Why this is non-negotiable

The factory's first text-input run emitted a Phase C report claiming
"0 raw colors" while 56 unbound white fills sat on every container
slot. They were invisible on the white page and obvious only when the
post-fix audit ran. "I think I did the right thing" is not a quality
gate.

The same shape of failure repeated on the Nav Header factory run
(2026-05-22): the Phase C report passed the existing gates while
shipping (a) every auto-layout frame's vertical padding as raw `8px` /
`12px` literals despite horizontal padding being correctly bound to
`uds-space-200` / `uds-space-150`, (b) every elevated surface as a
raw `node.effects = [...]` literal whose values didn't even match
the design system's `depth-100` and `depth-300` effect styles, and
(c) every nested icon-wrapper instance defaulted to the same
factory placeholder (`add_circle_outline`) including the title-area
chevron-slot, the search-icon, and every page-menu row — none of which
had been re-defaulted per the Phase A model's per-variant icon plan.
Checks 3, 4, and 5 above exist to make those three specific failure
modes machine-detectable rather than designer-detectable.

## 3. Variant grid layout reflects the variant axis's semantic intent

When the factory positions variants on the page (the visual grid a
designer scans when opening the component page), the layout strategy
depends on **what each variant axis means**.

### Per-column packing for size axes

If one variant axis varies a **size-related property** (height, density,
padding scale, type ramp step), pack each column independently. Each
column's variants stack at their own actual heights, so the SHORTER
column visibly ends earlier than the TALLER column. The size
differentiation reads at the column level, not just inside each cell.

```
sm column: variants at y = 0, 36, 72, 108, ...     (sm is 36px tall)
md column: variants at y = 0, 48, 96, 144, ...     (md is 48px tall)
```

### Max-per-row packing for non-size axes

If the variant axes are non-size (state, theme, emphasis, tone), then
max-per-row alignment is fine. md/Default sits next to sm/Default at
the same y, both in cells sized to the max height for that row.

### Why this matters

Max-per-row alignment across a Size axis makes md and sm columns
visually equalize because the row cells are forced to the same height.
The user-facing complaint from the first factory run was literally
"the sm and md seem to be the same height" even though the inner field
heights differed. Per-column packing eliminates that illusion.

## 4. Variant grid defaults show the component's standard anatomy

Visibility BOOLEAN defaults (`showLabel`, `showLeadingIcon`,
`showCounter`, `optional`, etc.) double as:

- **Per-instance defaults** — what designers get when they drop the
  component out of the asset picker.
- **Per-variant rendering** — what the variant grid on the component
  page shows.

For slots that are part of the component's **standard look** (leading
icon on a text input, anchor button on a dropdown, label on any form
input), default the BOOLEAN to `true`. The variant grid then renders
the full anatomy at every state, designers see what the component does
at a glance, and dropped instances arrive with the typical use already
configured.

For slots that are genuinely **optional adornments** (character
counter, trailing clear button, optional indicator), default to
`false`. Designers opt in when needed.

### Anti-pattern

Defaulting every `show*` BOOLEAN to `false` "to be conservative" makes
the variant grid render a stripped-down skeleton of the component. A
designer scanning the page sees seven near-identical empty fields and
has to manually toggle every variant to discover the component's
actual surface area. That's not conservative — it's hiding the design.

## 5. Build the dependency manifest before any write

Any factory build that nests other UDS components, binds tokens, or
applies text/effect styles needs to resolve every reference upfront.
Late-stage discovery wastes calls and creates ordering bugs.

### Required Phase B.0 (read-only)

A single `use_figma` call that returns one structured object containing:

- **Local nested-component IDs** — every UDS primitive the build will
  instantiate (e.g. `udc-icon-wrapper` set ID, default variant ID, key;
  same for `udc-label`, `udc-button-ghost`, `udc-support_required-dot`,
  etc.). For a labeled field/control, `udc-label` IS one of these — its
  label is a nested, forwarded `udc-label` instance, not raw text (§9).
- **Library variable KEYs** — every token the build will bind (color,
  border, space, font, radius).
- **Library style KEYs** — every text style and effect style the build
  will apply.

Stored in the model file at
`.cursor/state/component-factory/<componentId>.md` under a
`Dependencies` section, and re-imported at the top of every subsequent
Phase B call.

### Anti-pattern

Discovering a new dependency in the middle of a Phase B build (e.g.
realizing you need `border-tertiary` for Read-only after you've already
combined the variants into a set) means an extra read call, an extra
import call, and re-touching variants that should have been already
done. The first factory run did this for icon-wrapper, label,
button-ghost, and required-dot separately — four discovery calls that
should have been one.

### Why one upfront manifest works

Variable keys, style keys, and component KEYs are stable for the
duration of a factory run. Once collected, they can be passed as a
constant map to every `use_figma` call:

```js
const DEPS = {
  variables: { surfaceMain: '929a0f30897b12884c1848b5071f7ab3e0a31b72', ... },
  textStyles: { labelBaseMedium: '13846140fda29ad416db52e33809812769cb8a8b', ... },
  effectStyles: { /* ... */ },
  components: { iconWrapperSetId: '5745:4541', iconWrapperDefaultId: '5657:6767', ... }
};
```

Each Phase B call re-imports the variables/styles it needs by KEY
and re-fetches local components by node ID. No script writes raw hex
or hard-coded styling.

## 6. Tone-bearing adornments resolve to each variant's tone

When a component has a `Tone` / status / emphasis variant axis, EVERY
color-carrying adornment inside it — status dot, secondary or leading
icon glyph, trend indicator, accent bar — must be re-bound **per
variant** to that variant's tone token. A factory that builds one base
variant and clones it across tones carries the base's single tone into
every clone unless each adornment is explicitly re-bound.

Failure mode: the Metric Card factory baked the trend indicator
`success` (green) on the base, cloned it across all five tones, and
re-tinted only the chip / dot / main glyph — so the Error-tone card
shipped a green trend with no way to change it from the panel.

Rules:

- **Re-bind every tone-bearing adornment per variant**, not just the
  primary surface. Bind to that tone's family: `text-{tone}` /
  `icon-{tone}` / `surface-{tone}` (Neutral → `*-secondary`,
  Disabled → `*-disabled`).
- **Set semantic / directional glyph defaults per tone** where the
  glyph carries meaning: a trend defaults to `trending_up` for positive
  tones (Neutral / Info / Success) and `trending_down` for negative
  tones (Warning / Error); a status icon defaults to `check_circle` for
  Success, `error` for Error, etc.
- **Context-appropriate default glyphs, not the wrapper's stock
  placeholder.** A nested `udc-icon-wrapper` left at its default ships
  the same `add_circle_outline` plus everywhere. Pick a glyph that fits
  the demo content (a leads metric → `people_outline`; a revenue metric
  → `payments`; a trend → the directional arrow above). That default is
  the starting point the exposed control
  ([`uds-figma-plugin-api-gotchas.mdc`](./uds-figma-plugin-api-gotchas.mdc)
  §12) hands the designer.
- **If color or direction is genuinely independent of tone** (a trend
  can fall on a Success card), don't hardcode it — expose a control (a
  `Direction` variant or a property) and record it in the Phase A
  model. The default still follows tone; the control lets a designer
  override.

### Not every icon follows tone the same way — content vs control

Color an icon by what it *means*. A field carries two kinds of icon and
they react to tone differently:

- **Content / contextual icons** — a leading search glyph, a field's
  descriptive icon. These belong to the field's content layer and follow
  the **full tone**: Error → `icon-error`, Disabled → `icon-disabled`,
  Read-only → `icon-secondary` (muted). If the value text goes
  `text-error`, the content icon goes `icon-error` with it. Leaving it
  neutral while the border, label, and text are all red reads as
  disconnected.
- **Control affordances** — a chevron, a clear / dismiss button, a
  stepper caret. These are about *interaction*, not *validity*, so they
  follow whether the field is **usable**, not whether it's **valid**:
  - Error → **unchanged** (stay `icon-interactive` / neutral). A red
    chevron signals nothing useful; validity is carried by the border,
    label, value text, and message — not the controls.
  - Disabled → `icon-disabled` (a disabled field greys everything,
    controls included).
  - Read-only → hidden or muted (the control isn't operable).

Rule of thumb: **Error tone splits the icons (content follows, controls
don't); Disabled tone hits everything.** This was the combobox
2026-06-08 miss — every icon (leading glyph, clear, chevron) was pinned
to `icon-interactive` across all states, so the chevron stayed bright
blue on a disabled field and the leading search glyph stayed blue in
error.

### Inverse / saturated surfaces flip EVERY foreground

Tone is one axis; surface saturation is another. The split above governs
*which tone* an adornment takes. This governs what happens when a state
**fills** the element. Any state whose surface becomes
`surface-interactive-default` / `-active` / `-hover`, a prominent
`surface-{tone}`, or `surface-inverse` — selected, pressed, open,
checked, primary-at-rest — flips the WHOLE foreground to the inverse
family at once: text → `text-inverse`, and icons / chevrons / dots →
`icon-inverse`. Not just the label. A glyph left at `icon-interactive`
(or any light token) on a saturated fill disappears into the background
— the recurring nav-header 2026-06-16 failure across the selected menu
row, the pressed tile, and the open title-area.

Two corollaries the factory must hold:

- **Scope matches the node.** Icons bind `icon-inverse` (SHAPE_FILL),
  text binds `text-inverse` (TEXT_FILL). `text-inverse` on an icon looks
  right and is wrong — cross-scoped and fragile.
- **Detect the backing surface, not a sibling.** Decide an icon needs
  inverse by resolving the fill of the element it actually sits on (own
  box or nearest surface-painting ancestor), never "is there inverse text
  somewhere in this component." A white count on a red badge inside a
  light pill is not the leading glyph's background — that inference
  blanked the My-Work `+` (white-on-white) on 2026-06-16.

The canonical statement lives in
[`uds-design-language.mdc`](./uds-design-language.mdc) §4.1.

This is the color / glyph analogue of §2 check 5 (per-variant
INSTANCE_SWAP defaults): the wiring being present is not enough; each
variant's tone-bearing parts must actually resolve to that variant's
meaning. §2 check 6 makes it machine-detectable.

## 7. Secondary affordances use the right emphasis and default glyph

When a component nests a multi-emphasis sibling (most commonly a
Button) for a UTILITY affordance — an overflow menu, a dismiss button,
an inline card action — the factory must pick the emphasis that matches
the affordance's prominence, not the factory's default.

Rules:

- **Utility/secondary affordances take the LOW-emphasis set.** An
  overflow menu or dismiss control is a `udc-button-ghost` (or
  tertiary) icon-only instance, never `udc-button-primary`. A filled
  accent button demands attention that a utility control should not —
  it competes with the component's actual content.
- **Set a context-appropriate default glyph**, never the icon wrapper's
  stock placeholder. Overflow → `more_vert` (or `more_horiz`); dismiss
  → `close`; expand → `expand_more`. The placeholder
  `add_circle_outline` on a non-add control is always wrong.
- **This generalizes §6's glyph rule from icons to nested buttons.**
  The same "context-appropriate default, not the stock placeholder"
  discipline applies to every nested DS instance that carries meaning,
  whether it's a bare `udc-icon-wrapper` or a button that contains one.

Failure mode: the Metric Card overflow shipped as a
`udc-button-primary` (filled accent) carrying the `add_circle_outline`
placeholder glyph — wrong emphasis AND wrong glyph on a control that
should read as a quiet three-dots ghost button. The fix swapped it to
`udc-button-ghost` icon-only with a `more_vert` default.

## 8. One concern per axis — State stays interaction-only

Each variant axis encodes exactly ONE concern. A variant value that
changes the component's *interaction or selection state* (Default /
Hovered / Focused / Pressed / Selected / Disabled / Loading / Empty /
Error) belongs on the `State` axis — and only those belong there. Every
other concern is its own axis:

| Concern | Axis (example) | Values |
|---|---|---|
| Interaction / selection state | `State` | Default · Hovered · Focused · Pressed · Selected · Disabled · Error · Empty (the canonical set, naming §1) |
| Disclosure (open vs closed) | `Open` (boolean) | False · True |
| Content / data presence | `Filled` (boolean) or `Variant` | False · True, or Empty · Results |
| Kind / mode / purpose | `Kind` / `Type` / `Mode` | Metric · Add; Leaf · Parent · Child; Display · Editing (a view-vs-edit `Mode` axis) |
| Size | `Size` | Small · Medium · Large (naming §2) |
| Tone / status | `Tone` | Neutral · Info · Success · Warning · Danger (naming §3) |

Why it matters:

- Overloading `State` with another concern makes the axis lie: a
  designer scanning the `State` dropdown reads `Add` as if it were an
  interaction state of a populated card, or `Open-Empty` as if "open"
  were a state — when each is really a separate dimension.
- It corrupts the state-coverage reasoning: the class-required state
  baseline (§ skill State matrix) is computed against real states; a
  mode or a disclosure value masquerading as a state inflates or
  distorts that count.
- A mushed axis can't be machine-checked against the canonical state
  vocabulary, and the contract block's `States` section stops meaning
  anything.

**The compound-value smell test.** A variant value that joins two
concerns with a hyphen — `Open-Empty`, `Open-Typed`, a `Closed` sitting
beside `Open-*` — is the dead giveaway of a mushed axis: two dimensions
wearing one name. Split it. A hyphen isn't *always* a mush
(`Parent-collapsed` is one legitimate `Kind` value), so the gate splits
hard from soft: a hyphen on the `State` axis is a hard fail (canonical
states never contain one); a hyphen on any other axis is a soft review
flag (naming-convention gate, §2).

Failure modes:

- **Metric Card** carried `Add` as a `State` value beside `Default` /
  `Hover` / `Empty`. `Add` is a distinct add-a-metric affordance, not a
  state of an existing metric — it was moved to a `Kind = Metric | Add`
  axis, leaving `State` to genuine states.
- **global-search (2026-06-09)** carried `State = Closed | Open-Empty |
  Open-Typed` — three concerns (disclosure, content presence,
  interaction) jammed into one axis. It was split into `Open`
  (False/True, disclosure), the trigger's `State`
  (Default/Hovered/Focused, interaction) + `Filled` (False/True, content
  presence), and the popover's `Variant` (Empty/Results, content).
- **data-field (2026-06-10)** carried `State = Default | … | Editing`.
  `Editing` is a *mode* — the field viewing its value vs. showing its
  inline editor — not an interaction state; it was split onto a `Mode`
  axis (`Display | Editing`), leaving `State` to genuine states. The
  same build also buried `Empty` as a behavioral, non-drawable prop even
  though `Empty` is a canonical *drawable* conditional state (the "—"
  placeholder), so it was promoted to a real `State` variant. Two
  lessons: a single non-canonical word on `State` is a mode/disclosure
  in disguise (the §2 membership check, not the hyphen test, is what
  catches it); and a canonical *drawable* state (Empty / Read-only /
  Loading / Error) declared behavioral-only is a smell — draw it or
  justify why not.

When in doubt, ask: "is this the same component *reacting*, a *different
thing* the component can be, whether it's *open*, or whether it *has
content*?" Reacting → `State`. Different thing → `Kind`. Open →
disclosure axis. Has content → content axis.

### State coverage is per interactive Kind, not global

Once a component has BOTH a `Kind` / `Type` / `Mode` axis AND a `State`
axis, the class-required state baseline applies to **each interactive
Kind**, not to the set as a whole. "The `State` axis contains `Selected`
*somewhere*" is not coverage — the question is whether each Kind that a
user can select, press, or disable actually carries those states.

The nav-header 2026-06-16 draft shipped this gap: leaf items had the full
state set, but `Kind=Parent-collapsed` / `Parent-expanded` were missing
`Selected` and `Disabled`, and the expanded parent had no `Hovered`. Each
kind of menu row is independently interactive, so each needed the
baseline — the partial coverage read as "this component is done" while
half its kinds couldn't show selection or disablement.

Rule: compute the required-state baseline (per the component class) and
apply it to every interactive Kind. A Kind that genuinely can't take a
state marks it `notApplicable` with a reason (a static `Kind=Divider`
takes no states); silent omission for one Kind while another has the
state is the smell. The skill's State-matrix model step and the Phase C
"Class-required state coverage" gate both reason per (Kind × State) cell
when a Kind axis is present — see
[`generate-uds-figma-component`](../skills/generate-uds-figma-component/SKILL.md)
§"State matrix (class-driven)".

## 9. Form components nest the Label component — and forward its properties

A labeled field or control (text-input, dropdown, combobox, text-area,
search, checkbox, radio, toggle, switch, … — anything whose anatomy
includes a label tied to a control) renders its label as a **nested
`udc-label` instance**, not raw text. This is the §"Sibling reuse" rule
applied: `udc-label` already owns the label's editable text, the
required / optional indicators, the leading-icon and right-slot
(badge) affordances, and the tone colors. Rebuilding any of that as raw
nodes strands those features and lets the label's text style drift.

But nesting alone is not enough. The 2026-06-08/09 combobox proved both
failure modes:

1. **Nested-but-unforwarded** (the original defect). The label was a
   nested `udc-label`, but none of its properties were reachable from
   the combobox's right panel — the consumer couldn't edit the label
   text, toggle required, or set the icon/badge. A nested label whose
   properties aren't forwarded is barely better than raw text.
2. **Host-owned overcorrection** (the wrong fix). Replacing the nested
   label with a raw TEXT node "to avoid drift" threw away every one of
   those properties — editable text, required, optional, leading icon,
   right-slot badge — and would force rebuilding all of them in every
   field. That's a regression dressed as a simplification.

The standard is **nest AND forward**. The earlier drift (label at
`paragraph/sm-medium` 12 px instead of `label/base-medium` 14 px) was
never caused by nesting — it was the draft `udc-label` itself binding
the wrong text style. Fix the label component once, and every field
that nests it inherits the fix.

### What "nest and forward" means concretely

- The label region is an `INSTANCE` of `udc-label` parented at the top
  of the host's anatomy (a `udc-support_required-dot` primitive may
  still be nested inside the label as its own dot — that's the label's
  internal business).
- The nested label's properties are **reachable by the consumer**:
  either set `isExposedInstance = true` on the instance (surfaces
  text / required / optional / leading-icon / right-slot under the
  label section in the right panel), OR hoist the key ones (at minimum
  `text`, ideally `required`) to top-level component properties on the
  host set. Exposure is the simpler, complete default; hoist when the
  host already hoists sibling text props (the combobox hoists
  `helperText`, so hoisting `Label` text matches that convention).
- The nested label's **`tone` tracks the host's state**: the Error
  variant drives `tone=Error` (red + bold via `label/base-bold`),
  Disabled drives `tone=Disabled` (greyed). The label component owns
  the per-tone text style + color; the host only selects the tone.
- The `udc-label` component itself must bind a `uds/text/label/*` style
  (`label/base-medium` default, `label/base-bold` for the Error tone).
  If it's bound to a `paragraph/*` or other family, that's a bug in the
  label component — fix it there, not by abandoning nesting.

### Keep the standalone Label correct and reusable

Because every field nests it, `udc-label` is high-leverage: one fix
propagates everywhere. It also still serves the standalone case — a
label not wired to a built-in field (a group/section heading, a label
over a custom or non-UDS control). Don't strand it, don't duplicate it,
and don't silently drop its property surface when improving it (diff
the successor's `componentPropertyDefinitions` against the original — a
rebuild missing a slot or tone is a regression, not an improvement).

## 10. A field's popover / menu is an overlay anchored to the field

When a field opens a menu, listbox, calendar, or any popover (combobox,
select, dropdown, autocomplete, date-picker, …), the open surface is an
**overlay anchored to the field** — NOT an in-flow sibling stacked after
the helper row.

In real behavior the menu pops directly under the field and floats over
whatever sits below it (the helper text, the page content). Modeling it
as the next in-flow child after the helper row pushes the menu *below*
the helper, leaving an awkward gap with the helper text wedged between
the field and its own menu. That was the combobox 2026-06-08 open-state
miss (field bottom y72 → helper y76 → menu y92).

### The Figma construction

- The listbox/menu is `layoutPositioning = 'ABSOLUTE'` on the variant
  frame, anchored at the field's bottom edge (`y = field.y +
  field.height + gap`, `x = field.x`), width matched to the field
  (`constraints = { horizontal: 'STRETCH', vertical: 'MIN' }`).
- Because it's absolute, it does NOT push the helper row — the helper
  stays in flow under the field and the open menu overlays on top of it,
  exactly as it renders in the browser.
- `clipsContent = false` on the variant so the overlay renders past the
  collapsed auto-layout bounds.
- Reordering the menu to sit in-flow directly under the field with the
  helper pushed *below the menu* is NOT the fix — it relocates the helper
  between closed and open and still treats the menu as flow content.
  Anchor it as an overlay.

This is the same "pure overlay, anchored to its box, never changes the
flow" principle as the focus ring (§1) — a popover and a focus ring are
both overlays on the field, not members of its layout stack. §2 check 10
makes it machine-detectable.

## 11. Form controls conform to the shared field-metrics contract

Fields and form controls aren't sized in isolation — they bind to the
design system's single field-metrics contract so a form of mixed controls
lines up and every control clears the touch-target minimum. For UDS that
contract is [`uds-design-language.mdc`](./uds-design-language.mdc) §10
("Field & control metrics contract").

The load-bearing idea: **what aligns is the control _container_, not the
visible control.** A text field fills the shared container height; a
checkbox / radio / toggle centers a smaller visible control inside the
same container. So the factory sizes the container to the contract and
centers the control — it never stretches a checkbox to the field height.

Rules:

- **Read the contract in Phase A.** When the component's class is a field
  or form control, bind the Phase A model's container height, label
  style, helper style, and label/helper gaps to the design-language
  field-metrics values — don't re-derive them per component (that's how
  the fields drifted before the contract existed).
- **Container height, not visible-control height.** Size the alignment /
  touch container to the contract (48 px for UDS) and vertically center
  the visible control. A control whose visible box is stretched to the
  container height (a giant checkbox), or whose container is shorter than
  the contract (a ~24 px checkbox that breaks alignment + touch), both
  fail.
- **Label is the shared nested `udc-label`** (per §9), at the contract's
  label style — never a per-control raw text style.
- **Font scale, density, and mobile are out of scope for the per-control
  build.** Font scale (`larger`/`default`/`smaller`) and density
  (`comfortable`) are runtime user settings; mobile is form-level layout.
  Author the one canonical control at **default** scale and density —
  never per-scale/density variants, and never bake a non-default resolved
  px (e.g. the larger-scale 16px input) in as "the" value. See
  [`uds-design-language.mdc`](./uds-design-language.mdc) §10 "Design at
  default scale and density."

§2 check 11 makes conformance machine-detectable.

## 12. Action pairs — Cancel + primary order and alignment

When a component nests a confirm / dismiss button pair — Cancel + Save,
Cancel + Apply, an inline editor's save/cancel — two construction rules
apply, and the factory must enforce both:

- **Primary goes on the right, dismiss on its left.** Save / Apply /
  Confirm (the primary) is the right-most button; Cancel (the secondary
  / ghost) sits to its left. This is the UDS dialog footer convention
  ("the primary action sits bottom-right, secondary to its left" —
  `dialog/spec.json`) and the Button guidance ("Cancel on the left,
  primary on the right" — `button/spec.json`). It is not dialog-only —
  any nested Cancel + primary pair follows it. Cancel stays
  ghost / secondary: discarding an in-progress edit is not a destructive
  action and gets no danger treatment (UDS has no Danger tone — naming
  §3).
- **The action row matches the control it sits under.** When the pair
  sits beneath a full-width control (an inline editor's input, a dialog
  body), the row must `layoutSizingHorizontal='FILL'` to the control's
  width and right-align its cluster (`primaryAxisAlignItems='MAX'`), so
  the primary's right edge lands on the control's right edge. A row left
  in `HUG` + `MIN` floats the primary mid-width, detached from the field
  edge — the data-field 2026-06-10 inline editor shipped exactly that (a
  248px hug row under a 260px input, Save stranded in the middle) until
  it was caught by eye, not by a gate.

The skill's Phase C action-pair gate makes both machine-detectable: for
any nested Cancel + primary button pair it flags (a) the primary not
being right-most, and (b) a pair-bearing row that hugs / left-aligns
under a wider sibling control instead of filling + right-aligning.

## 13. Recurring visual affordances belong in the component, not the composition

A visual treatment that repeats across instances — a nesting / indent
guide rail, a tree connector, a status accent bar, a grouping divider —
must be **baked into the source component (or variant)**, never
hand-placed as a free-floating absolute node in the assembled
composition. A rail dropped as an absolute rectangle into the nav-list
instance is brittle: it doesn't reflow when rows are added or reordered,
it doesn't travel when the component is reused elsewhere, and it has to
be re-drawn by hand every time. Built into the Child variant, it's
intrinsic — every instance gets it for free and it tracks the row.

This is the same principle §1 states for focus rings and §10 for
popovers ("a pure overlay that lives in the box, anchored to it"),
generalized to *structural* treatments: if it's part of what the
component IS, it lives in the component.

### When a baked-in rail meets a full-width highlight, inset the highlight

A guide rail baked into a child variant collides with a full-width
hover / selected / focus highlight — the pill paints over the rail. The
fix is to **inset the highlight to clear the rail**, not to move the
rail back out to the composition. Move the highlight off the variant's
frame fill onto an inset `row-bg` rectangle (and inset the focus ring to
match) so the rail reads continuously down the nesting column while the
highlight sits inside it. The nav-header 2026-06-16 child rows did this:
rail at the variant's left edge, hover/selected `row-bg` and focus ring
inset to its right.

Failure mode (nav-header 2026-06-16): the nesting rail first shipped as
absolute rectangles placed in the nav-list composition. The designer
flagged it ("the rail should be baked into the subcomponent, not an
absolute-position treatment") — it was rebuilt into each Child variant,
and the child highlights were inset to clear it.

## 14. Cell content alignment — top-align icon-over-label cells, not center

When a fixed-height cell stacks a fixed-size element (an icon) over a
variable-length one (a label) — a quick-action tile, an icon grid cell,
a stat card — vertically centering the stack
(`primaryAxisAlignItems = 'CENTER'`) ties the icon's position to the
label's line count. A row that mixes one-line and two-line labels then
lands its icons at different heights, and the grid reads as misaligned
even though every cell carries identical alignment settings. Top-align
the stack (`primaryAxisAlignItems = 'MIN'`) so the icon sits at one
consistent position and the label hangs below; the price is extra bottom
whitespace under short labels, which is the conventional icon-grid look.

Set it on the source component / variant, not the instances, so every
cell inherits it and a later label edit can't reintroduce the drift.

### Alignment consistency is (alignment mode × child intrinsic size), not the alignment property alone

A uniform alignment enum across sibling cells does NOT guarantee aligned
content when the children differ in size — a centered stack with a taller
child sits its fixed element higher than a centered stack with a shorter
one. Diagnose "looks off" by reading the *variable child's size*, not by
eyeballing the render and not by confirming that the alignment enum
matches across cells. The factory check: for any repeating
icon-over-label cell, confirm the fixed element shares one position
across siblings (e.g. icon `y` is equal in every cell), not merely that
every cell says `CENTER`.

Failure mode (nav-header 2026-06-16): the quick-tile grid centered each
tile's icon+label stack, so one- and two-line labels put the icons at
different heights across the row. It was first misdiagnosed from the
render as a horizontal label-alignment problem before the real cause —
centered stacks over variable-height labels — was found and fixed by
top-aligning (`MIN`) the five tile variants.

